WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.100 --> 00:00:01.840
JONAH BERGER: So I want
to start with

00:00:01.840 --> 00:00:03.230
a very simple question.

00:00:03.230 --> 00:00:05.810
These are three products and
brands that most of you in the

00:00:05.810 --> 00:00:07.810
audience are probably
quite familiar with.

00:00:07.810 --> 00:00:10.220
So on the left we have Walt
Disney World, the

00:00:10.220 --> 00:00:13.280
self-described place where
dreams come true; in the

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:15.390
middle, we have Honey Nut
Cheerios, the delicious

00:00:15.390 --> 00:00:18.800
breakfast cereal, which may or
may not cure your cholesterol;

00:00:18.800 --> 00:00:20.830
and on the right we have
Scrubbing Bubbles, the

00:00:20.830 --> 00:00:22.170
bathroom cleaner.

00:00:22.170 --> 00:00:25.260
So if you had to guess, which of
these three products do you

00:00:25.260 --> 00:00:27.730
think gets the most
word of mouth?

00:00:27.730 --> 00:00:31.960
Is it Disney World, Cheerios,
or Scrubbing Bubbles?

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:33.400
And I'm actually going to
ask everybody to vote.

00:00:33.400 --> 00:00:35.325
So you want to take
a first guess?

00:00:35.325 --> 00:00:36.510
AUDIENCE: I'd say Scrubbing
Bubbles.

00:00:36.510 --> 00:00:36.870
JONAH BERGER: Scrubbing
Bubbles.

00:00:36.870 --> 00:00:39.200
How many people want to vote
for Scrubbing Bubbles?

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:39.820
OK.

00:00:39.820 --> 00:00:40.220
Good.

00:00:40.220 --> 00:00:42.580
Somebody else want to take
a different vote?

00:00:42.580 --> 00:00:43.020
Yeah.

00:00:43.020 --> 00:00:43.500
AUDIENCE: Disney World.

00:00:43.500 --> 00:00:44.040
JONAH BERGER: Disney World.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:46.260
How people want to
go with Disney?

00:00:46.260 --> 00:00:46.630
OK.

00:00:46.630 --> 00:00:47.610
Good.

00:00:47.610 --> 00:00:48.860
Anybody else?

00:00:51.160 --> 00:00:51.720
That's it.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:52.203
OK.

00:00:52.203 --> 00:00:53.170
AUDIENCE: I gotta
say Cheerios.

00:00:53.170 --> 00:00:53.830
JONAH BERGER: Okay, you'll
say Cheerios.

00:00:53.830 --> 00:00:54.740
You'll be the brave soul.

00:00:54.740 --> 00:00:55.210
OK, good.

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:55.970
AUDIENCE: Come on Cheerios.

00:00:55.970 --> 00:00:56.930
JONAH BERGER: Cheerios.

00:00:56.930 --> 00:00:57.020
Good.

00:00:57.020 --> 00:00:59.920
I got a couple of people
for Cheerios.

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:01.200
So I want to point out
two things in this.

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:03.250
First, I don't think
we know the answer.

00:01:03.250 --> 00:01:06.150
So we went around, about, I'd
say about 45% of the folks

00:01:06.150 --> 00:01:08.550
were for Scrubbing Bubbles,
about 45%

00:01:08.550 --> 00:01:09.490
were for Disney World.

00:01:09.490 --> 00:01:11.750
So we're pretty evenly split
among those two.

00:01:11.750 --> 00:01:13.430
So we're not really sure
of the answer.

00:01:13.430 --> 00:01:15.690
But second, if we did have to
guess-- so how many people

00:01:15.690 --> 00:01:17.580
guessed Disney World?

00:01:17.580 --> 00:01:18.810
That is a really good guess.

00:01:18.810 --> 00:01:20.990
It's wrong, but good guess.

00:01:20.990 --> 00:01:23.000
Scrubbing Bubbles?

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.930
Also an excellent guess,
also wrong.

00:01:25.930 --> 00:01:28.620
So the gentleman over here who
is nice enough to stick his

00:01:28.620 --> 00:01:30.970
neck out for me, I appreciate
it, is actually--

00:01:30.970 --> 00:01:33.270
Cheerios gets more word of mouth
than Disney World and

00:01:33.270 --> 00:01:33.980
Scrubbing Bubbles.

00:01:33.980 --> 00:01:35.320
And this is just one example.

00:01:35.320 --> 00:01:38.950
But I think it points to a
broader question, which is why

00:01:38.950 --> 00:01:41.870
do some products and ideas get
talked about more than others?

00:01:41.870 --> 00:01:43.970
You probably heard that word of
mouth is really important,

00:01:43.970 --> 00:01:45.340
as we'll talk about in
next couple minutes.

00:01:45.340 --> 00:01:47.000
It's more important
than advertising.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.430
But to make it work, we have to
understand why people talk

00:01:49.430 --> 00:01:50.800
about some things rather
than others.

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:53.260
If we want people to talk about
our product or idea, we

00:01:53.260 --> 00:01:55.940
have to understand the science
or the psychology behind

00:01:55.940 --> 00:01:57.390
social transmission.

00:01:57.390 --> 00:01:59.670
And so that's what I'm going
to talk about today.

00:01:59.670 --> 00:02:00.640
My name is Jonah Berger.

00:02:00.640 --> 00:02:04.140
I'm a professor at the Wharton
School, I have this book

00:02:04.140 --> 00:02:06.280
called "Contagious," which
is coming out tomorrow.

00:02:06.280 --> 00:02:08.410
I have heard that they've been
nice enough to get some of

00:02:08.410 --> 00:02:09.949
them for you guys at
a reduced cost.

00:02:09.949 --> 00:02:11.800
But they're actually
unfortunately not here today.

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:13.300
So if you're interested, they'll
be here tomorrow

00:02:13.300 --> 00:02:15.970
apparently or you can
get it on Amazon or

00:02:15.970 --> 00:02:16.890
anywhere else you want.

00:02:16.890 --> 00:02:17.870
It'll be in stores tomorrow.

00:02:17.870 --> 00:02:18.980
I'm excited to actually
physically

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:19.760
see it in the store.

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:21.810
So tomorrow will be
exciting day.

00:02:21.810 --> 00:02:23.040
Also, everything I'm
going to talk about

00:02:23.040 --> 00:02:25.130
today is research based.

00:02:25.130 --> 00:02:26.900
It would be great to be
a social media guru.

00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:28.470
I think it's a really fun job.

00:02:28.470 --> 00:02:30.500
Apparently, all you have
to do is make guesses

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:31.490
about what's true.

00:02:31.490 --> 00:02:33.760
You don't have to back it up
with data and you just get to

00:02:33.760 --> 00:02:34.300
write about it.

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:35.630
And that sounds fantastic.

00:02:35.630 --> 00:02:36.890
But that's actually
not my job.

00:02:36.890 --> 00:02:39.090
Wharton would not pay
me if I did that.

00:02:39.090 --> 00:02:41.500
So all this is based on academic
research that we and

00:02:41.500 --> 00:02:43.540
others have done in the
past decade or so.

00:02:43.540 --> 00:02:44.740
It's all up on my website.

00:02:44.740 --> 00:02:46.970
If you're interested, please
go check it out.

00:02:46.970 --> 00:02:49.200
And that'll sort of fill in a
lot of the gaps from what I'm

00:02:49.200 --> 00:02:51.570
going to talk about today.

00:02:51.570 --> 00:02:54.220
So just to start us out with
that idea that word of mouth

00:02:54.220 --> 00:02:57.480
is important, McKinsey, none
other than McKinsey, because

00:02:57.480 --> 00:02:59.933
people believe what McKinsey
says, has said that word of

00:02:59.933 --> 00:03:01.980
mouth generates more than
twice the sales of paid

00:03:01.980 --> 00:03:04.810
advertising in categories as
diverse as skin care and

00:03:04.810 --> 00:03:06.010
mobile phones.

00:03:06.010 --> 00:03:08.730
And this probably doesn't come
as a big surprise to folks in

00:03:08.730 --> 00:03:11.840
the audience, but a lot of
research in the past decade or

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:13.310
so has shown that word
of mouth has a big

00:03:13.310 --> 00:03:15.420
causal impact on sales.

00:03:15.420 --> 00:03:18.220
Everything you can imagine, from
online book reviews, so a

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:21.090
five-star review, increases the
number of books sold by

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:24.890
about 20, to offline word of
mouth for restaurants and a

00:03:24.890 --> 00:03:26.460
whole host of other products.

00:03:26.460 --> 00:03:28.810
Why do you think that word
of mouth is so much more

00:03:28.810 --> 00:03:31.570
effective than advertising,
if you had to guess?

00:03:31.570 --> 00:03:31.860
Yeah?

00:03:31.860 --> 00:03:33.340
AUDIENCE: It's usually
a trusted source.

00:03:33.340 --> 00:03:33.950
JONAH BERGER: OK.

00:03:33.950 --> 00:03:35.890
So we don't really believe
advertising.

00:03:35.890 --> 00:03:38.150
Advertisers say hey, 9 out
of 10 dentists love this

00:03:38.150 --> 00:03:38.800
toothpaste.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:39.850
You say hold on.

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:40.240
Really?

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:41.150
9 out of 10 dentists.

00:03:41.150 --> 00:03:42.350
I don't know about that.

00:03:42.350 --> 00:03:44.660
You never see an ad that says 1
out of 10 dentists like this

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:45.360
toothpaste, right?

00:03:45.360 --> 00:03:47.990
So you don't trust ads, but
you trust your friends.

00:03:47.990 --> 00:03:50.280
Your friends usually have your
best interests at heart.

00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:51.220
They're going to help you.

00:03:51.220 --> 00:03:51.680
That's good.

00:03:51.680 --> 00:03:52.640
That's one reason.

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:55.560
The other reason is word of
mouth is much more targeted.

00:03:55.560 --> 00:03:58.830
And now with digital ad
targeting, a lot of the good

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:01.520
work that Google's doing, it's
easier to target people.

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:03.935
But it's still really hard to
be exactly sure what someone

00:04:03.935 --> 00:04:05.400
is interested in and
when they might be

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:07.020
interested in that thing.

00:04:07.020 --> 00:04:09.140
So if you sell skis for example,
well maybe you say,

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:10.820
OK, I'm going to buy some words

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:13.030
related to skis on keywords.

00:04:13.030 --> 00:04:14.130
That'll get you sort of close.

00:04:14.130 --> 00:04:15.370
Because it may not be
still people who are

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:16.640
looking to buy skis.

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:19.310
Maybe you get buy skis and
that's even closer.

00:04:19.310 --> 00:04:21.690
Or you average in a ski
magazine, but a whole bunch of

00:04:21.690 --> 00:04:23.660
people who are reading that
magazine might not actually be

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:25.530
in the market for skis
at the moment.

00:04:25.530 --> 00:04:28.720
So what word of mouth does is
it's really, really targeted.

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:31.070
So if you don't have a baby,
no one's going to tell you

00:04:31.070 --> 00:04:31.970
about baby products.

00:04:31.970 --> 00:04:34.490
If you don't like spicy food, no
one's going to talk to you

00:04:34.490 --> 00:04:36.880
about a restaurant that has
really great spicy food.

00:04:36.880 --> 00:04:38.980
Word of mouth is like a
searchlight that works through

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:41.760
your social network to find the
person that might be most

00:04:41.760 --> 00:04:44.120
interested in a particular
product or idea.

00:04:44.120 --> 00:04:45.820
So a really nice example of
this that happened to me a

00:04:45.820 --> 00:04:48.350
couple years ago, publishers
often send academics

00:04:48.350 --> 00:04:49.530
books in the mail.

00:04:49.530 --> 00:04:51.540
They're hoping that we'll read
those books and assign them to

00:04:51.540 --> 00:04:52.810
our classes.

00:04:52.810 --> 00:04:54.850
And so I got a book in the
mail from a publisher.

00:04:54.850 --> 00:04:56.800
But they didn't actually send
one, they actually sent two

00:04:56.800 --> 00:04:59.800
books, two copies of
the same book.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:01.690
Now let me tell you, the second
copy is not any better

00:05:01.690 --> 00:05:02.240
than the first.

00:05:02.240 --> 00:05:03.660
It was the exact same book.

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:04.540
So why would they do that?

00:05:04.540 --> 00:05:06.230
Well, they sent that second book
and they said Professor

00:05:06.230 --> 00:05:08.190
Berger, we think you'll
like this book.

00:05:08.190 --> 00:05:10.320
And if you do, please share it
with a friend of yours might

00:05:10.320 --> 00:05:11.630
like it as well.

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:12.360
And so that's this old

00:05:12.360 --> 00:05:13.970
sociological idea of homophily.

00:05:13.970 --> 00:05:16.660
We tend to be friends of people
that are similar to us.

00:05:16.660 --> 00:05:18.010
If you like football,
you tend to have

00:05:18.010 --> 00:05:19.110
friends who like football.

00:05:19.110 --> 00:05:21.520
If you like opera, you tend to
have friends that like opera.

00:05:21.520 --> 00:05:24.030
And so if you like something,
you probably know other people

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:25.940
that would like that as well.

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:29.000
And that's the targeting benefit
of word of mouth and

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.275
social media more generally,
finding people that are going

00:05:31.275 --> 00:05:33.880
to interested in it, who can
help you find other people

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:35.150
that are interested in it.

00:05:35.150 --> 00:05:37.430
That's why the referral benefits
are so useful.

00:05:37.430 --> 00:05:39.960
The customer lifetime value of
customers referred through

00:05:39.960 --> 00:05:42.540
social networks is much higher
than traditional customers

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:44.680
because it helps people find the
people that will be most

00:05:44.680 --> 00:05:45.730
interested.

00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:46.270
OK, great.

00:05:46.270 --> 00:05:47.690
So we like word of mouth.

00:05:47.690 --> 00:05:48.670
Let's jump on the bandwagon.

00:05:48.670 --> 00:05:50.100
How do we get it?

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:52.930
And indeed, there's been a lot
of interest lately in social

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:54.100
media channels.

00:05:54.100 --> 00:05:55.930
If you had to guess though, how
much word of mouth do you

00:05:55.930 --> 00:05:57.595
think is over social media?

00:05:57.595 --> 00:06:01.280
So it's over things like
Facebook, like Twitter, online

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:01.760
interviews.

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:05.280
What percent of word of mouth is
online, compared to offline

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:07.134
being face to face?

00:06:07.134 --> 00:06:08.040
AUDIENCE: 20.

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:09.010
JONAH BERGER: 20.

00:06:09.010 --> 00:06:11.920
20.

00:06:11.920 --> 00:06:12.890
AUDIENCE: 25.

00:06:12.890 --> 00:06:14.345
JONAH BERGER: 25.

00:06:14.345 --> 00:06:14.840
AUDIENCE: 5.

00:06:14.840 --> 00:06:15.230
JONAH BERGER: 5.

00:06:15.230 --> 00:06:16.110
We'll do---

00:06:16.110 --> 00:06:16.860
AUDIENCE: 40.

00:06:16.860 --> 00:06:17.160
JONAH BERGER: 40.

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:18.210
I feel like auctioneer up here.

00:06:18.210 --> 00:06:19.490
10?

00:06:19.490 --> 00:06:21.040
Do I hear 20, 25, 30, 30?

00:06:21.040 --> 00:06:23.210
It's actually 7.

00:06:23.210 --> 00:06:25.500
So not 70, not 17, 7.

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:27.410
So the 5 was pretty close.

00:06:27.410 --> 00:06:30.210
And if we think about why that
is though, we can think about

00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:31.920
why we think there's so much
online word of mouth.

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:34.300
Hardly a the day goes by where
we see an article, like we

00:06:34.300 --> 00:06:36.250
don't see an article about it
in the paper, oh Facebook is

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:38.920
doing this, Twitter is doing
this, Google+ is doing this.

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:41.220
There's some new site we need
to pay attention to.

00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:43.300
And further there's a
record of all the

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:44.420
things we share online.

00:06:44.420 --> 00:06:46.690
We can go back and look at
those things we shared.

00:06:46.690 --> 00:06:48.660
But if you think about what
you did in the five or 10

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:50.770
minutes before you were waiting
for me to talk or even

00:06:50.770 --> 00:06:52.570
when you were out in the
hallway, you were probably

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:54.200
talking to someone else
and you were probably

00:06:54.200 --> 00:06:55.720
talking face to face.

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:57.280
You don't sit in a meeting
and tweet back and

00:06:57.280 --> 00:06:58.470
forth to each other.

00:06:58.470 --> 00:07:00.400
You have a face-to-face
conversation.

00:07:00.400 --> 00:07:03.280
And so much more word of mouth
is actually offline.

00:07:03.280 --> 00:07:06.590
And I think the second problem
with focusing so much on these

00:07:06.590 --> 00:07:08.450
is we think about the technology
rather than the

00:07:08.450 --> 00:07:09.480
psychology.

00:07:09.480 --> 00:07:11.300
So everyone probably
remembers Myspace.

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:13.070
A few years ago, you could have
decided you're going to

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:14.060
be a Myspace expert.

00:07:14.060 --> 00:07:16.510
You're going to put all your
eggs in the basket of Myspace,

00:07:16.510 --> 00:07:17.460
understand how it works.

00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:18.460
That's great.

00:07:18.460 --> 00:07:21.280
And now how useful would
that expertise be?

00:07:21.280 --> 00:07:21.720
AUDIENCE: Not really.

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:23.080
JONAH BERGER: Not
really, right?

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:24.490
We've moved on to
something else.

00:07:24.490 --> 00:07:27.360
And so if Facebook is here in
10 years, maybe, maybe not.

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:28.910
Twitter is here in 10 years,
maybe, maybe not.

00:07:28.910 --> 00:07:30.150
A couple of years ago,
it was Foursquare

00:07:30.150 --> 00:07:31.240
was the new hot thing.

00:07:31.240 --> 00:07:32.930
Now, everyone's talking
about Pinterest.

00:07:32.930 --> 00:07:34.800
Technologies will come and go.

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:38.010
Why people share things will
pretty much stay the same, the

00:07:38.010 --> 00:07:40.520
same psychological drivers
of sharing.

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:42.820
And so we need to understand
why people talk and share.

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:45.100
And that brings me
to this picture.

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:47.790
This is a cat playing
a turntable.

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:48.940
It's not actually a turntable.

00:07:48.940 --> 00:07:51.490
It's a sort of cat
scratching post.

00:07:51.490 --> 00:07:54.540
But anyone have any idea why
I have this in my talk?

00:07:54.540 --> 00:07:59.590
Why a talk on virality has to
have a picture of cats in it.

00:07:59.590 --> 00:08:00.222
What?

00:08:00.222 --> 00:08:01.400
AUDIENCE: People share
them a lot.

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:01.690
JONAH BERGER: Yeah.

00:08:01.690 --> 00:08:04.230
So there's a theory out there
that people share things

00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:06.190
because they have pictures
of cats in them.

00:08:06.190 --> 00:08:09.080
So you go on the web, one of
the most prevalent theories

00:08:09.080 --> 00:08:09.970
oh, why do things go viral?

00:08:09.970 --> 00:08:12.030
Because of cats.

00:08:12.030 --> 00:08:14.070
So this cat picture
is fantastic.

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:16.850
It's got to go viral because
it has cats in it.

00:08:16.850 --> 00:08:18.420
Now, obviously that
logic is flawed.

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:19.810
It's flawed for a
couple reasons.

00:08:19.810 --> 00:08:22.260
First, it's like noticing that
Bill Gates, Bill Clinton, and

00:08:22.260 --> 00:08:24.390
Bill Cosby are all famous.

00:08:24.390 --> 00:08:27.220
And so you decide to name your
child Bill because well,

00:08:27.220 --> 00:08:30.550
getting the name Bill must be
