00:17:45.990 --> 00:17:48.810
And this searches for Rebecca
Black over time.

00:17:48.810 --> 00:17:50.870
What you notice is it
goes up, big spike.

00:17:50.870 --> 00:17:53.515
So then it tails off,
less interest.

00:17:53.515 --> 00:17:56.860
Then it goes up again,
down, up again.

00:17:56.860 --> 00:17:57.800
There's a spike.

00:17:57.800 --> 00:17:58.860
You probably can't see it.

00:17:58.860 --> 00:18:02.390
But it's a spike every
seven days.

00:18:02.390 --> 00:18:05.450
Every seven days is a
spike in attention.

00:18:05.450 --> 00:18:08.470
Now, this song is equally bad
every day of the week.

00:18:08.470 --> 00:18:09.210
I checked.

00:18:09.210 --> 00:18:11.450
I've listened to it on Monday,
Tuesday, Wednesday, Thursday,

00:18:11.450 --> 00:18:13.760
Saturday, Sunday, and
Friday, equally bad.

00:18:13.760 --> 00:18:17.460
Yet Friday is an environmental
reminder to think about that

00:18:17.460 --> 00:18:19.580
song and to share
it with others.

00:18:19.580 --> 00:18:21.460
And that's what I'll
call a trigger.

00:18:21.460 --> 00:18:23.690
It's a cue, a stimulus in the
environment that triggers us

00:18:23.690 --> 00:18:25.480
to think about something else.

00:18:25.480 --> 00:18:28.050
And maybe you hear that
something is top-of-mind, like

00:18:28.050 --> 00:18:30.550
Friday makes us think about
Rebecca Black's song, it's

00:18:30.550 --> 00:18:32.020
going to be tip-of-tongue.

00:18:32.020 --> 00:18:33.835
Not only are you going to be
more likely to watch that song

00:18:33.835 --> 00:18:36.420
or purchase a product if it is
a product, but you're gong to

00:18:36.420 --> 00:18:38.250
be more likely to share it
with others because it's

00:18:38.250 --> 00:18:39.610
top-of-mind.

00:18:39.610 --> 00:18:42.480
So usage is one thing that
makes a product or idea

00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:43.370
top-of-mind.

00:18:43.370 --> 00:18:45.770
By top-of-mind, I basically what
are you thinking about?

00:18:45.770 --> 00:18:47.870
So right now, you're probably
thinking about hopefully the

00:18:47.870 --> 00:18:50.350
talk, what you just had for
lunch, or what you're doing

00:18:50.350 --> 00:18:51.000
afterwards.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:52.460
You're probably not really
thinking about what you're

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:54.280
going to for summer vacation or
what you're going to do for

00:18:54.280 --> 00:18:54.800
the holidays.

00:18:54.800 --> 00:18:57.220
Those things are lower
down on your list.

00:18:57.220 --> 00:18:59.120
But using a product is one
thing that can make it

00:18:59.120 --> 00:19:00.580
top-of-mind.

00:19:00.580 --> 00:19:04.180
This is Twitter traffic for
Cheerios by time of day.

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:06.790
And not rocket science, what
you see is not much around

00:19:06.790 --> 00:19:07.890
midnight, 2:00 AM, 4:00 AM.

00:19:07.890 --> 00:19:09.550
6:00 AM, it starts going up.

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:12.300
Around 8:00 AM, lots of people
are talking about Cheerios.

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:14.085
Then it goes down again
throughout the day.

00:19:14.085 --> 00:19:15.910
And what that's saying
is people eat

00:19:15.910 --> 00:19:16.700
Cheerios in the morning.

00:19:16.700 --> 00:19:18.070
It's making that product
top-of-mind.

00:19:18.070 --> 00:19:20.470
It's making it more likely to
talk about it and share it.

00:19:20.470 --> 00:19:22.055
Notice what happens
on the weekend?

