And if you don't eat Cheerios,
you wheel your cart through

00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:01.580
the grocer isle and see that
box once or twice a week.

00:20:01.580 --> 00:20:03.690
And because you're seeing it,
it's more top-of-mind.

00:20:03.690 --> 00:20:05.500
And you might say well hold on,
is usage is the only thing

00:20:05.500 --> 00:20:07.290
that makes a product
top-of-mind?

00:20:07.290 --> 00:20:09.020
So do related cues.

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:11.430
So if I said peanut
butter and--

00:20:11.430 --> 00:20:12.310
jelly, right?

00:20:12.310 --> 00:20:13.440
Or if I said rum and--

00:20:13.440 --> 00:20:13.990
AUDIENCE: Coke.

00:20:13.990 --> 00:20:15.010
JONAH BERGER: Coke.

00:20:15.010 --> 00:20:18.010
Notice that the word jelly and
the word Coke aren't up there.

00:20:18.010 --> 00:20:19.740
But the word peanut butter
is like a little

00:20:19.740 --> 00:20:21.690
advertisement for jelly.

00:20:21.690 --> 00:20:23.400
If someone says cat,
you think of dog.

00:20:23.400 --> 00:20:25.360
If someone says peanut butter,
you think of jelly.

00:20:25.360 --> 00:20:28.650
It triggers related ideas in our
minds because those things

00:20:28.650 --> 00:20:29.760
are connected.

00:20:29.760 --> 00:20:32.620
Michelob used this idea of a
couple years ago with their

00:20:32.620 --> 00:20:35.620
slogan, "Weekends are Made for
Michelob." Their idea was hey,

00:20:35.620 --> 00:20:36.640
we're going to link the product

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:38.340
to a time, the weekend.

00:20:38.340 --> 00:20:40.260
So when the weekend rolls
around, people hopefully think

00:20:40.260 --> 00:20:41.940
about consuming the product.

00:20:41.940 --> 00:20:43.860
Every time the weekend rolls
around and I want a beer, I'm

00:20:43.860 --> 00:20:45.220
going to think about Michelob.

00:20:45.220 --> 00:20:47.150
Corona has tried to do the same
thing with the beach.

00:20:47.150 --> 00:20:49.560
When you're on a beach vacation,
it's really hard not

00:20:49.560 --> 00:20:51.150
to think about ordering
Corona.

00:20:51.150 --> 00:20:52.620
You have to sort of stop
yourself and say hold on, I

00:20:52.620 --> 00:20:54.150
should order something else.

00:20:54.150 --> 00:20:56.660
But they have done a really good
job of owning the beach.

00:20:56.660 --> 00:20:58.160
Beer and the beach, you
think about Corona.

00:20:58.160 --> 00:20:59.320
Weekends and the beach,
hopefully

00:20:59.320 --> 00:21:01.310
you think about Michelob.

00:21:01.310 --> 00:21:03.900
So in terms of applying this
concept, you need to consider

00:21:03.900 --> 00:21:04.970
the context.

00:21:04.970 --> 00:21:07.280
You think about the cues or
triggers that are around your

00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:09.660
consumers that they
might come around.

00:21:09.660 --> 00:21:13.070
So one of my favorite examples
of this comes with cats.

00:21:13.070 --> 00:21:15.250
So if you a the cat and your cat
is hungry, what's your cat

00:21:15.250 --> 00:21:16.890
going to say?

00:21:16.890 --> 00:21:21.140
Meow, which is why Meow Mix is
a great name for a cat food.

00:21:21.140 --> 00:21:23.260
Every time your cat goes meow,
you're more likely to think

00:21:23.260 --> 00:21:24.630
about that thing.

00:21:24.630 --> 00:21:26.260
But you need to think
about your specific

00:21:26.260 --> 00:21:27.550
customers, your consumers.

00:21:27.550 --> 00:21:30.000
So there's a restaurant in
Philadelphia called Barclay

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:32.640
Prime that has a $100
cheesesteak.

00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:34.830
A $100 cheesesteak, right?

00:21:34.830 --> 00:21:37.650
It has Kobe beef, it has
lobster, it has truffles.

00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:39.680
It comes with a little
bottle of champagne.

00:21:39.680 --> 00:21:42.680
Basically, the most opulent
thing you can think of.

00:21:42.680 --> 00:21:45.630
Huge, hugely expensive, I
