00:32:37.731 --> 00:32:40.186
AUDIENCE: I'm curious about your
study on "The New York

00:32:40.186 --> 00:32:41.659
Times" [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:41.659 --> 00:32:42.641
shared.

00:32:42.641 --> 00:32:46.620
So given that there's some use
triggers where they're not--

00:32:46.620 --> 00:32:48.962
I don't think social like cachet
would necessarily apply

00:32:48.962 --> 00:32:50.360
to a lot of the article.

00:32:50.360 --> 00:32:52.690
What were some of the triggers
that apply to

00:32:52.690 --> 00:32:53.700
"The New York Times"?

00:32:53.700 --> 00:32:55.050
JONAH BERGER: So we found a
number of different things.

00:32:55.050 --> 00:32:56.640
And if you're interested, the
article is up on my website

00:32:56.640 --> 00:32:57.770
and we talk about
it in the book.

00:32:57.770 --> 00:32:58.500
We found a few things.

00:32:58.500 --> 00:33:00.790
So one, there is some social
currency in sharing.

00:33:00.790 --> 00:33:02.030
People are more likely to
share interesting or

00:33:02.030 --> 00:33:04.130
surprising things because
it makes them look good.

00:33:04.130 --> 00:33:06.570
There's also a lot of practical
value, so restaurant

00:33:06.570 --> 00:33:08.770
reviews, movie reviews.

00:33:08.770 --> 00:33:10.550
If you ever see the articles
that come out in education

00:33:10.550 --> 00:33:11.000
aren't many.

00:33:11.000 --> 00:33:13.990
But tips for choosing colleges,
people love that.

00:33:13.990 --> 00:33:17.040
One big thing in practical value
is six tips for this.

00:33:17.040 --> 00:33:18.330
I call it the "Cosmo" effect.

00:33:18.330 --> 00:33:20.280
If you ever looked at "Cosmo"
when you're in the line at the

00:33:20.280 --> 00:33:22.840
grocery store, and most men's
magazines do it as well, but

00:33:22.840 --> 00:33:25.500
six secrets for this, seven
ways to do this.

00:33:25.500 --> 00:33:27.830
Articles that really boil down
concepts into useful

00:33:27.830 --> 00:33:29.620
information get shared a lot.

00:33:29.620 --> 00:33:31.940
But then we also found emotion
was a big driver.

00:33:31.940 --> 00:33:34.660
And not just positive emotion,
also negative emotions if

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:35.920
they're high arousal.

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:37.700
So if you think about both
positive and negative

00:33:37.700 --> 00:33:41.860
emotions, they can be divided
not only into whether their

00:33:41.860 --> 00:33:43.300
valence is positive
or negative.

00:33:43.300 --> 00:33:47.490
So happiness or humor is
a positive emotion.

00:33:47.490 --> 00:33:49.580
Anger or sadness is a
negative emotion.

00:33:49.580 --> 00:33:51.650
But also whether they're
high or low arousal.

00:33:51.650 --> 00:33:54.620
So anger and sadness are
both negative emotions.

00:33:54.620 --> 00:33:56.850
Neither fear is really good,
but anger is activating

00:33:56.850 --> 00:33:59.550
emotion and sadness is a
deactivating emotion.

00:33:59.550 --> 00:34:00.410
So you think about
what you do.

00:34:00.410 --> 00:34:01.990
When you're angry, you want
to yell at someone.

00:34:01.990 --> 00:34:03.380
You want to throw something.

00:34:03.380 --> 00:34:05.330
You're mad, you're shaking
your fists.

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:06.940
When you're sad,
what do you do?

00:34:06.940 --> 00:34:09.060
You of curl up under the
covers, you put on your

00:34:09.060 --> 00:34:11.760
favorite sweat shirt, eat
a big bowl of ice cream.

00:34:11.760 --> 00:34:13.590
You sort of shut off
from the world.

00:34:13.590 --> 00:34:15.630
And so what we found is it's not
only whether the articles

00:34:15.630 --> 00:34:18.010
are positive or negative, but
also at the high arousal,

00:34:18.010 --> 00:34:20.230
activating, or low arousal,
deactivating.

00:34:20.230 --> 00:34:22.260
We actually found anything
that deactivates actually

00:34:22.260 --> 00:34:23.670
decreases sharing.

00:34:23.670 --> 00:34:25.510
So even merely the act of
running in place, so we've

00:34:25.510 --> 00:34:27.090
done experiments where we have
people run in place in the

00:34:27.090 --> 00:34:29.510
laboratory, that increases the
likelihood of emailing

00:34:29.510 --> 00:34:31.900
articles to others, even if
those articles have nothing to

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:33.300
do with the running in place.

00:34:33.300 --> 00:34:34.880
Because it activates the body.

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:37.840
That physiological system gets
going and they infer that then

00:34:37.840 --> 00:34:39.179
the content must be
worth sharing.

00:34:39.179 --> 00:34:40.909
So that's just some of
the things we found

00:34:40.909 --> 00:34:42.810
from the Times analysis.

00:34:42.810 --> 00:34:44.547
Other-- yeah?

