AUDIENCE: On the social media
track-- email, and the chat,

00:35:14.035 --> 00:35:15.318
and all that--

00:35:15.318 --> 00:35:18.760
so in your research, like how
much do you think that that

00:35:18.760 --> 00:35:22.952
factors in or doesn't in
how we share things?

00:35:22.952 --> 00:35:25.694
Like how important is that?

00:35:25.694 --> 00:35:28.180
Are we skewed because we can
track the social media stuff

00:35:28.180 --> 00:35:28.860
that Twitter basically is?

00:35:28.860 --> 00:35:29.370
JONAH BERGER: Yeah.

00:35:29.370 --> 00:35:31.690
So I think that's one we reason
that we focus so much

00:35:31.690 --> 00:35:32.530
on the online.

00:35:32.530 --> 00:35:34.860
We say OK, we can see it.

00:35:34.860 --> 00:35:37.110
And I'm actually working on an
op-ed for "The New York Times"

00:35:37.110 --> 00:35:37.480
for this weekend.

00:35:37.480 --> 00:35:39.890
But think about just how
statistics or measuring things

00:35:39.890 --> 00:35:41.920
affect our behavior.

00:35:41.920 --> 00:35:43.830
So take Facebook, for example.

00:35:43.830 --> 00:35:45.190
Facebook made the number
of friends we

00:35:45.190 --> 00:35:46.490
have a thing to count.

00:35:46.490 --> 00:35:48.740
Well, now we all want that
number to be higher.

00:35:48.740 --> 00:35:50.170
You think about the Prius,
the Prius came out.

00:35:50.170 --> 00:35:52.020
We used to care about
how fast a car went.

00:35:52.020 --> 00:35:53.930
Now, they display
the gas mileage.

00:35:53.930 --> 00:35:55.150
The gas mileage has
always been there.

00:35:55.150 --> 00:35:57.420
But now that we can see it,
we care a lot about it.

00:35:57.420 --> 00:35:59.650
Because we can say oh, I want to
get my gas mileage higher.

00:35:59.650 --> 00:36:01.530
I want to get my Twitter
followers higher because more

00:36:01.530 --> 00:36:02.390
must be better.

00:36:02.390 --> 00:36:04.520
And so merely measuring things
can actually change our

00:36:04.520 --> 00:36:06.330
behavior in relation
to those things.

00:36:06.330 --> 00:36:07.900
And I think social
is the same way.

00:36:07.900 --> 00:36:09.320
We can see it online.

00:36:09.320 --> 00:36:10.520
And I'm all about measurement.

00:36:10.520 --> 00:36:11.360
I'm a data guy.

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:12.130
I like measuring things.

00:36:12.130 --> 00:36:13.400
I'm not saying we shouldn't
measure things.

00:36:13.400 --> 00:36:15.990
But we should be careful how
merely measuring things can

00:36:15.990 --> 00:36:17.190
change our behavior.

00:36:17.190 --> 00:36:18.780
And just because we're measuring
something, doesn't

00:36:18.780 --> 00:36:20.120
mean we're measuring
the right thing.

00:36:20.120 --> 00:36:21.700
So we've done some work
with offline word

00:36:21.700 --> 00:36:22.340
of mouth, as well.

00:36:22.340 --> 00:36:24.990
So there's a company called
Keller Fay that records lots

00:36:24.990 --> 00:36:26.690
of-- asks people to keep
diaries of offline

00:36:26.690 --> 00:36:28.030
conversations.

00:36:28.030 --> 00:36:30.560
Some smart academics have put
together a device called the

00:36:30.560 --> 00:36:32.560
EAR, electronically activated
recorder.

00:36:32.560 --> 00:36:33.670
Basically you can carry
it around with you.

00:36:33.670 --> 00:36:36.000
It records ambient noise
throughout the day.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.110
So it can get a chance of what
you're talking about

00:36:38.110 --> 00:36:40.710
throughout the day, even if
you're not writing it online.

00:36:40.710 --> 00:36:44.360
And so I think there are ways
to measure offline behavior.

00:36:44.360 --> 00:36:46.500
But there's always a focus
on what's online.

00:36:46.500 --> 00:36:48.470
I think the important thing
here is we've done

00:36:48.470 --> 00:36:49.450
some of the leg work.

00:36:49.450 --> 00:36:51.230
So some companies say well hold
on, we want to test every

00:36:51.230 --> 00:36:51.900
single campaign.

00:36:51.900 --> 00:36:53.260
How can we test offline
sharing?

00:36:53.260 --> 00:36:54.360
How can we measure it?

00:36:54.360 --> 00:36:56.250
And what we can say is well,
look, we've actually looked at

00:36:56.250 --> 00:36:56.820
offline sharing.

00:36:56.820 --> 00:36:58.240
We've done a lot of research
in this space.

00:36:58.240 --> 00:36:59.990
If you follow these principles,
your stuff will be

00:36:59.990 --> 00:37:00.990
shared more.

00:37:00.990 --> 00:37:02.050
You don't necessarily
have to do the

00:37:02.050 --> 00:37:03.310
groundwork all over again.

00:37:03.310 --> 00:37:04.930
But I agree, certain things
are definitely harder to

00:37:04.930 --> 00:37:08.300
measure in this space.

00:37:08.300 --> 00:37:10.610
Anybody else?

00:37:10.610 --> 00:37:11.920
Yeah?

00:37:11.920 --> 00:37:13.460
AUDIENCE: Cats?

00:37:13.460 --> 00:37:15.430
JONAH BERGER: Oh, why cats?

00:37:15.430 --> 00:37:17.950
So I'm an academic.

00:37:17.950 --> 00:37:18.860
Academics tend to be
a little bit of

00:37:18.860 --> 00:37:20.530
curmudgeons, so oh, cats.

00:37:20.530 --> 00:37:22.810
So I used to say, oh, it's
not actually true.

00:37:22.810 --> 00:37:23.780
And I thought about
it a little more.

00:37:23.780 --> 00:37:26.510
I was going to write an op-ed
about cats versus dogs.

00:37:26.510 --> 00:37:29.170
And I have an answer that's less
satisfying to me, but I

00:37:29.170 --> 00:37:30.570
think is more true.

00:37:30.570 --> 00:37:32.720
So one, I think there
are more cat people.

00:37:32.720 --> 00:37:36.190
Cat owners I think are more
into their cats than dog

00:37:36.190 --> 00:37:36.320
owners are.

00:37:36.320 --> 00:37:37.550
Everyone's into their pets.

00:37:37.550 --> 00:37:38.220
It's like your kids.

00:37:38.220 --> 00:37:39.260
Why do you show photos
of your kids?

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:39.850
Look at my kid.

00:37:39.850 --> 00:37:40.700
They did this.

00:37:40.700 --> 00:37:41.780
They made this great picture.

00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:42.490
You show it to all
your friends.

00:37:42.490 --> 00:37:43.510
And they're like what is that?

00:37:43.510 --> 00:37:46.130
It's like macaroni on like
a piece of cardboard.

00:37:46.130 --> 00:37:47.530
But yeah, because my kid,
my kid made this.

00:37:47.530 --> 00:37:48.140
It's great.

00:37:48.140 --> 00:37:50.480
So the same thing with cats
and dogs in general.

00:37:50.480 --> 00:37:52.760
I think cat people are maybe a
little bit more engaged with

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:54.660
their-- dog people are a more
like this is my dog.

00:37:54.660 --> 00:37:56.668
But cat people are like
this is my cat.

00:37:56.668 --> 00:37:58.010
I'm so excited.

00:37:58.010 --> 00:37:59.910
Having spent though
unfortunately, fortunately or

00:37:59.910 --> 00:38:02.890
unfortunately, an hour looking
at cat photos and videos last

00:38:02.890 --> 00:38:04.240
week and thinking about whether
I could write this

00:38:04.240 --> 00:38:07.540
editorial, I think that cats
are actually not more

00:38:07.540 --> 00:38:11.380
photogenic, but they have more
of a varieties of faces and

00:38:11.380 --> 00:38:14.490
things that make them amenable
to the phrases that people put

00:38:14.490 --> 00:38:16.030
on those pictures.

00:38:16.030 --> 00:38:19.160
So they really make themselves
amenable to whatever we want

00:38:19.160 --> 00:38:21.210
to call them, the I Can
Has Cheezburger?

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:23.450
Or you know, I mean your fridge,
eating your foods.

00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:24.610
There's things we put on them.

00:38:24.610 --> 00:38:27.610
If you look at those for dogs,
they're just not like "as

00:38:27.610 --> 00:38:33.670
good." So I wouldn't think that
per cat piece, cats are

00:38:33.670 --> 00:38:35.930
more likely to be shared
that a given dog piece.

00:38:35.930 --> 00:38:38.000
But I think that more cat
pieces are created just

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:40.600
because they're sort of more
leeway to do those things.

00:38:40.600 --> 00:38:42.660
Whether it's a cat hanging on
its hind legs looking like

00:38:42.660 --> 00:38:45.600
it's from "Thriller" or a cat
that is like Hoover Cat,

00:38:45.600 --> 00:38:47.250
there's all sorts of these
different things.

00:38:47.250 --> 00:38:49.220
I think dogs generally
look happy.

00:38:49.220 --> 00:38:50.130
And I have a dog myself.

00:38:50.130 --> 00:38:51.240
I'm a dog person.

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:52.560
So I'm very dismayed
that people

00:38:52.560 --> 00:38:54.200
share lots of cat things.

00:38:54.200 --> 00:38:56.740
But dogs sort of have the happy
look and the sort of

00:38:56.740 --> 00:38:57.750
dumb, out of it look.

00:38:57.750 --> 00:38:59.130
My dog has both of them.

00:38:59.130 --> 00:39:01.240
Whereas cats do more angry.

00:39:01.240 --> 00:39:02.670
They do different
sorts of things.

00:39:02.670 --> 00:39:05.450
And I think that's really
amenable to those phrases,

00:39:05.450 --> 00:39:07.140
which itself is a little bit
of internet culture.

00:39:07.140 --> 00:39:08.830
I think that's a great example
of social currency.

00:39:08.830 --> 00:39:10.080
Why do people do that?

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:11.770
What do they riff off
existing photos?

00:39:11.770 --> 00:39:14.610
There's a recent one you might
have seen with a pigeon with

00:39:14.610 --> 00:39:16.420
bread around, a bread crust
around it's neck.

00:39:16.420 --> 00:39:18.920
Have you seen that one, where it
says swag underneath, which

00:39:18.920 --> 00:39:20.620
I think is just great.

00:39:20.620 --> 00:39:21.720
But it's sort of showing
that you know

00:39:21.720 --> 00:39:22.750
what's going on in culture.

00:39:22.750 --> 00:39:24.970
You can riff off it and
create something new.

00:39:24.970 --> 00:39:26.700
And so I think that's a driver
of a lot of those.

00:39:26.700 --> 00:39:30.068
Why cats I think, I think cats
are quite photogenic.

00:39:30.068 --> 00:39:32.219
AUDIENCE: Well, you listed the
question about why there's

00:39:32.219 --> 00:39:34.370
more cat media up there
than say dog media--

00:39:34.370 --> 00:39:34.820
JONAH BERGER: Yes.

00:39:34.820 --> 00:39:36.260
AUDIENCE: --but not why
it's shared more.

00:39:36.260 --> 00:39:37.470
JONAH BERGER: So I'm not
actually-- so sorry.

00:39:37.470 --> 00:39:39.910
To be clear, shared more in
aggregate is different than

00:39:39.910 --> 00:39:41.440
likelihood of sharing.

00:39:41.440 --> 00:39:44.060
So there's 1,000 pieces of cat
stuff and there's 100 pieces

00:39:44.060 --> 00:39:47.380
of dog stuff, cat stuff may have
more aggregate shares,

00:39:47.380 --> 00:39:49.210
even though the likelihood of
sharing given seeing one of

00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:50.680
those is lower.

00:39:50.680 --> 00:39:53.690
So you'd have to be 10 times as
likely share the dog stuff

00:39:53.690 --> 00:39:54.960
for aggregate shares--

00:39:54.960 --> 00:39:57.210
if there's 1/10 the dog stuff,
you gotta be 10 times likely

00:39:57.210 --> 00:39:58.020
to share it.

00:39:58.020 --> 00:40:00.100
I'm not convinced that you are
more likely to share a piece

00:40:00.100 --> 00:40:01.150
of cat content.

00:40:01.150 --> 00:40:03.740
But I think people are more
likely to create cat content.

00:40:03.740 --> 00:40:06.520
And so the overall aggregate
sharing of cat content is

00:40:06.520 --> 00:40:07.860
higher, even though
the likelihood--

00:40:07.860 --> 00:40:09.730
if you sent me a piece of cat
content and you sent me a

00:40:09.730 --> 00:40:11.300
piece of dog content,
the likelihood of

00:40:11.300 --> 00:40:13.040
sharing it might be equal.

00:40:13.040 --> 00:40:16.050
But I have not empirically
looked at that, even though it

00:40:16.050 --> 00:40:17.455
is a fun thing to empirically
look at.

00:40:17.455 --> 00:40:18.670
AUDIENCE: So this is now your
next piece of research.

00:40:18.670 --> 00:40:19.320
JONAH BERGER: Ah, yes.

00:40:19.320 --> 00:40:21.470
I should rigorously examine
cat versus dog,

00:40:21.470 --> 00:40:23.292
cat versus dog things.

00:40:23.292 --> 00:40:24.645
AUDIENCE: Well, if you
do, that certainly

00:40:24.645 --> 00:40:25.550
will be best seller.

00:40:25.550 --> 00:40:26.800
JONAH BERGER: Yes.

00:40:28.910 --> 00:40:30.120
It's emotion in one
of those things.

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:31.280
We care about our cats.

00:40:31.280 --> 00:40:33.200
We like to show our cats
doing funny things.

00:40:33.200 --> 00:40:35.650
And we like to show we're in the
loop, which I think both

00:40:35.650 --> 00:40:39.190
relates to social currency
and emotion.

00:40:39.190 --> 00:40:40.410
Anything else?

00:40:40.410 --> 00:40:41.380
OK, thank you guys for coming.

00:40:41.380 --> 00:40:42.850
I will stay up here, if there
are any more questions.

00:40:42.850 --> 00:40:44.100
Otherwise, have a good day.

